The two similes identify the posture of Geryon in terms of
homely images, a boat drawn up to shore, a beaver fishing with its
tail.  (Beavers were reputed to use their tails as bait, eventually
grasping the fish thereby attracted with their paws.)  Tommaseo (comm.
to vv. 19-21) pointed out that hyperactive Teutonic appetite was a
matter of note as far back as in the histories of Tacitus.
