..TEXT:
Icarus (Ovid, ^Metam~. VIII.183-235), on a second
extraordinary flight that failed, did not obey the instructions of his
father, Daedalus, trying instead to turn a voyage home into a trip
through the galaxy.  If the protagonist then thought of these two
precursors, he must have thought that he, too, might die for his
temerity; the poet, however, making the analogies now, sees the comic
resolution of a voyage that might have turned tragic except for the
fact that this voyager had God on his side.
